&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h1 id="the-80-hour-myth"&gt;The 80-hour Myth&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nov 29 2005&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s get serious. Nobody works eighty hours a week. Not eighty real, productive hours. Look closely at workaholics (and I&amp;rsquo;ve been one, and worked with ones), and a lot of the time is spent idling, re-charging, cycling, switching gears, etc. In the old days this was water-cooler talk. In Silicon Valley, it&amp;rsquo;s gaming, email, IM, lunches, and idle meetings. Let&amp;rsquo;s drop the farce, ok? Even when you had to work eighty hours, you didn&amp;rsquo;t, really. In economic terms, there is lower diminishing marginal productivity beyond some point. This point hits differently for different problems (some, like software engineering, require a lot of startup time to load a complex problem into your working memory).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>